view of the Red Cross, describes the book in his Foreword as 'an invaluable contribution to a better understanding of the role that criminal law can play in efforts to enhance respect for the rights of victims of violence and war'. This title in the Melland Schill Studies in International Law series is a useful text for all those who wish to understand the principles of criminal responsibility in international humanitarian law.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 7aLAW / Environmental.2bisacsh  aICC.  aInternational Criminal Court.  aInternational Criminal Tribunal for Rwanda.  aInternational Criminal Tribunal for Yugoslavia.  aMelland Schill.  aPaul Reuter Prize winner.  acrimes against humanity.  adirect criminal responsibility.  agenocide.  ainternal armed conflicts.  ainternational law.  apersonal responsibility.  asuperior responsibility.  awar crimes.1 aBantekas, Ilias, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb40uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/978152617055240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781526170552423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781526170552/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles